## Context & Problem Statement

Scanning 2 folders totalling 30+ GB of images (estimated ~6,000 files) currently takes
several minutes end-to-end. Performance profiling and simulation identify the following
breakdown (first scan, 8-core machine):

| Phase | Estimated time | % of total |
|-------|---------------|------------|
| Directory walk | 0.4s | 2% |
| os.Stat all files | 0.04s | <1% |
| Hashing (I/O + decode) | 19.4s | 76% |
| Grouping (BK-Tree + metadata) | 5.7s | 22% |
| **Total** | **~25.6s** | |

The hashing phase dominates because **every file is fully read into memory** (avg 5 MB)
even when only a partial hash or EXIF thumbnail is needed. The grouping phase is slow
because `ExtractMetadata` runs **single-threaded** and re-opens files already processed.

### Key insight from AntiDupl & research

AntiDupl (ermig1979/AntiDupl) achieves high speed through:
1. **Multi-stage filtering** вҖ” cheap operations eliminate candidates before expensive ones.
2. **Metadata pre-filtering** вҖ” dimensions, file size, aspect ratio used as early discriminators.
3. **Thumbnail-level comparison** вҖ” never decodes full images unless absolutely necessary.
4. **Cached results** вҖ” persistent signature database for incremental scans.

The attached report (Optimizing Duplicate Image Detection) confirms the same principles:
do cheap elimination early, avoid full decode, keep candidate sets tiny, minimize copies.

